(IMO, I think an argument could be make this is a JDK bug. Given my (limited) understanding of x.509 I would've expected the verification to be handled automatically behind the scenes and by default. Especially given the proposed workaround above relies on using the identification algorithm of "HTTPS", which is clearly out of place in this context.

Relevant JDK source:
[X509TrustManagerImpl.java|http://www.docjar.com/html/api/sun/security/ssl/X509TrustManagerImpl.java.html] (line 346))

Values in an object returned from a query may be an empty object or an empty array.

If such cases, calling bo.keySet().isEmpty() always returns false (the result is hardwired in the method override), depsite the fact that bo.keySet().size() == 0.

A simple fix is to change the org.bson.util.StringRangeSet.isEmpty() implementation to:

    @Override
    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return size == 0;
    }

